2 birds seen. The first was seen flying at a distance for about a minute. Flight was flapping interspersed with gliding, which is when the cinnamon underwings were clearly seen. As well as dark leading edge of upper wings.  Light brown over all.  The 2 nd   Bird was seen walking near Canada geese and size was proportional to them, smaller but still hefty for a wader.  The long deceived bill seen on the second bird.  Both were lighter brown than what I would expect for a whimbrel and were at quite a distance, but we were confident of the ID.  The more lazy flight style we felt also ruled out marbled godwit.  The light was quite bright. Bill Tice

Large sandpiper with upturned beak.  Base was slightly pale, but overall impression was of a dark Bill.  Bill was shorter than on marbled.  Was shorter legged than adjacent whimbrels.  Barring on tail/rump clearly seen while preening.  Strong white supercilium. No cinnamon wing-linings seen whennit flew away.

Observation Details: Two tattlers seen on first island and 1 on 2nd island. Two on first island are very different from each other causing discussion of whether one is a Grey-tailed tattler. The much lighter colored bird had a light grayish-brown back and wings. Fine barring on breast, getting fainter towards belly. Very faint barring on sides below wings. There was a very distinct white eyebrows and a dark eyeline.. Slender beak about the same length as the head. Exhibited bobbing behavior similar to spotted sandpiper.  Darker bird showed extensive barring on breast and belly. Much darker color and less obvious eyebrow. A third bird was seen on the 2nd island seemed lighter in color similar to first bird, but was much further away and difficult to see details. Seen by group.
